However, existing paleoclimate evidence suggests global warming should eventually lead to a more El-Ni√±o-like climate state. We don‚Äôt know when such a shift from La-Ni√±a-like to El-Ni√±o-like trends will occur; this is a major source of uncertainty in regional climate trends.
These changes towards a more La-Ni√±a-like climate state are not captured by current climate models, which would bias their projections of shifts in rainfall.

An implication of our results is that the observed trends with more warming in the west than east Pacific (so-called La-Ni√±a-like warming) could be partially a response to anthropogenic forcing, contributing to the current 3-year La Ni√±a and impacting rainfall in many regions.

Using a novel pattern recognition method, we isolate the patterns that contribute most to the discrepancy between observations and models on long timescales, which could help identify which mechanisms are involved. https://t.co/J6aS4IO2z4

The trend bias could be a bias in the response to anthropogenic forcing in models, a bias in their internal variability, or a consequence of missing forcing (such as Antarctic meltwater). Our paper provides an extensive discussion of potential contributors to this discrepancy.

A key result is that none of the ~600 historical climate model simulations studied are able to simulate the observed magnitudes of both Pacific zonal SST gradient strengthening and Southern Ocean cooling. https://t.co/MsSExulcH3

We find that trends in many regions and large-scale climate indices are unlikely (<5% chance) to occur in climate models LEs. This indicates that there is a systematic bias in the large-scale SST (and sea-level pressure) trend patterns simulated by climate models.
LEs allow us to quantify the range of possible trends due to a combination of natural internal variability anthropogenic (and natural) forced responses.
